ter stemmer** is a classic algorithm for this. *(Note: Lemmatization is an alternative that finds grammatically correct base forms, but it is computationally heavier and often yields similar performance).*"],"metadata":{"id":"CuJ-bPJ-pgHB"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### Code: Tokenization and Porter Stemming"],"metadata":{"id":"Ujrd9ZO6vj12"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["# Basic tokenizer\n","def tokenizer(text):\n","    return text.split()\n","\n","print(tokenizer('runners like running and thus they run'))"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["['runners', 'like', 'running', 'and', 'thus', 'they', 'run']\n"]}],"execution_count":39,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"CFNqG8vXpgHB","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1780679517957,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":8,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"ed9949e0-d30e-4363-eeca-8a6f56c1b012"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["from nltk.stem.porter import PorterStemmer\n","\n","porter = PorterStemmer()\n","\n","def tokenizer_porter(text):\n","    return [porter.stem(word) for word in text.split()]\n","\n","print(tokenizer_porter('runners like running and thus they run'))"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"N4aVQsvFw3nJ","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1780679517963,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":4,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"8393e05d-c0af-4c38-b591-ea5b635458a6"},"execution_count":40,"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["['runner', 'like', 'run', 'and', 'thu', 'they', 'run']\n"]}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["---\n","\n","## 6. Stop Word Removal\n","\n","Stop words are extremely common words (e.g., *is, and, has, like*) that bear little useful distinguishing information. Removing them is particularly useful when working with raw term frequencies instead of TF-IDF."],"metada